<Section title = "Four-bar linkages">
        <p>
          A planar four-bar linkage consists of four rigid rods in the
          plane connected by pin joints. We call the rods:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Ground link <InlineEquation equation = "g:"/> fixed to anchor pivots <InlineEquation equation = "A"/> and <InlineEquation equation = "B."/></li>
          <li>Input link <InlineEquation equation = "a:"/> driven by input angle <InlineEquation equation = "\\alpha."/></li>
          <li>Output link <InlineEquation equation = "b:"/> gives output angle <InlineEquation equation = "\\beta."/></li>
          <li>Floating link <InlineEquation equation = "f:"/> connects the two moving pins <InlineEquation equation = "C"/> and <InlineEquation equation = "D."/></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          We often think of a four-bar linkage as being driven at the
          input angle <InlineEquation equation = "\\alpha,"/>, resulting in the output angle
          <InlineEquation equation = "\\beta."/> We only need one input, because the system has
          exactly <InlineEquation equation = "N_{\\rm DOF} = 1"/> degree of freedom. We can count
          the DOF as 9 free variables (three moving rigid bodies with
          three variables each) minus 8 constraints (four pin joints
          with two constraints each).
        </p>
        <table class="alignTop figureLeftControl">
          <tr>
            <td>
              <canvas id="aml-ft-c" width="600" height="300">
              </canvas>
            </td>
            <td class="controls">
              <button class="anim-toggle:aml-ft-c">animation</button>
              <button class="reset:aml-ft-c">reset</button>
              <table class="alignTop">
                <tr>
                  <td>Show:</td>
                  <td>
                    <button class="option-toggle:aml-ft-c:showLabels">labels</button>
                    <button class="option-toggle:aml-ft-c:showPivots">pivots</button>
                  </td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <table>
                <tr><td>Input \(\alpha\):</td><td><span class="data-option:aml-ft-c:inputType"></span></td></tr>
                <tr><td>Output \(\beta\):</td><td><span class="data-option:aml-ft-c:outputType"></span></td></tr>
              </table>
            </td>
          </tr>
        </table>
        <p>
          Four-bar linkages can be used for many mechanical purposes, including to:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>convert rotational motion to reciprocating motion (e.g., <a href="#aml-sp">pumpjack</a> examples below)</li>
          <li>convert reciprocating motion to rotational motion (e.g., <a href="#aml-sb">bicycle</a> examples below)</li>
          <li>constrain motion (e.g., <a href="#aml-sk">knee joint</a> and <a href="#aml-sw">suspension</a> examples below)</li>
          <li>magnify force (e.g., <a href="#aml-sj">parrotfish jaw</a> examples below)</li>
        </ol>
</Section>

<SubSection title = "Rotating cranks and reciprocating rockers" id = "rotating_cranks_and_reciprocating_rockers">
        <p>
          Four-bar linkages can convert between different types of
          motion. We call these:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>Crank rod: rotating motion through a complete circle.</li>
          <li>Rocker rod: reciprocating motion with a total angle less than <InlineEquation equation = "360 ^ \\circ"/></li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          On the linkage below, adjusting the lengths of the input rod
          <InlineEquation equation = "a"/> and the output rod <InlineEquation equation = "b"/> shows that we can have an input
          crank and output rocker or the other way around, depending
          on whether <InlineEquation equation = "a &lt; b"/> or <InlineEquation equation = "a &gt; b."/> The case when <InlineEquation equation = "a = b"/>
          is special.
        </p>
