            <button class="anim-toggle:aml-fb-c">animation</button>
            <button class="reset-time:aml-fb-c">reset</button>
          </p>
          <p class="figureCaption">
            A man riding a bicycle at the port of <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vannes">Vannes</a>,
            Brittany, in the north-west of France. Image source: <a
            href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/adulau/7705967112/">Flickr
            image</a> by <a
            href="http://www.flickr.com/people/adulau/">Alexandre
            Dulaunoy</a> (<a
            href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/2.0/deed.en">CC
            BY 2.0</a>) (<a href="aml_7705967112.jpg">full-sized
            image</a>).
          </p>
        </div>
        <p>
          While the four links in the bicycle linkage are
          approximately rigid rods, only two of the joints are in fact
          reasonable models of a pin joint (the knee and lower
          crank). At the pedal and seat, only compression is allowed,
          as there is no way for the rider to pull up on the pedal or
          seat. This doesn't normally matter, as the rider's weight
          serves to maintain the connection at the seat, while the
          pedal joint only has force exerted during the down-stroke on
          each side, and the two legs are offset by 180&#176; so one
          is always pushing down. An alternative approach is used on
          racing bikes, where the feet are clipped to the pedals and
          so each foot can pull up as well as push down.
          </p>
      <div class="infoCol">
        <div id="aml-ib" class="infoBox factBox">
          <p>
            While the current form of the bicycle may seem obvious,
            with a rotary crank connected by a chain to the rear
            wheel, it took over 50 years for it <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_bicycle">to
            be developed</a>. Before this time, many different systems
            for bicycle propulsion were tried. The <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laufmaschine">first
            bicycle</a>, invented by <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Drais">Karl
            Drais</a> in <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mannheim">Mannheim</a>,
            Germany in 1818, used direct human propulsion along the
            ground, as shown below.  Mannheim was an important
            location for vehicle invention, as it was also the city
            where <a href="avb.html#avb-is">Karl Benz invented the
            modern automobile in 1885</a>.
          </p>
          <div class="imageBox width250">
            <img src="aml_Draisine1817_clipped_small.jpg" alt="A Draisine bicycle."></img>
            <p class="caption">
              Image credit: <a
              href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Draisine1817.jpg">Wikimedia
              Commons</a> (<a
              href="http://creativecommons.org/licenses/publicdomain/">public
              domain</a>) (<a href="aml_Draisine1817.jpg">full-sized
              image</a>).
            </p>
          </div>
          <p>
            Later bicycle propulsion mechanisms used pedals directly
            attached to the hub of the front wheel (the so-called <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boneshaker_(bicycle)#Boneshaker">bone-shaker</a>),
            which caused difficulties in pedaling while turning. This
            direct drive also had gearing problems, as a comfortable
            ratio of pedal frequency to velocity required very large
            wheels, leading to the <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Penny-farthing">penny-farthing</a>. An
            alternative approach to cranks was to use <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treadle_bicycle">treadles</a>,
            allowing the pedals to be positioned away from the wheel
            hub. This series of inventions finally resulted in the <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Safety_bicycle">safety
            bicycle</a> in 1876, which is the modern form we still use
            today.
          </p>
