              DOI: <a href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1098/rstb.1996.0065">10.1098/rstb.1996.0065</a>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div> 
      <div class="infoCol">
        <div id="aml-ij" class="infoBox factBox">
          <p>
            Parrotfish have two sets of jaws: the regular set of oral
            jaws that we can see, and a second set of <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharyngeal_jaw">pharyngeal
            jaws</a> located at the start of their throat (the <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pharynx">pharynx</a>). The
            pharyngeal jaws are used to crush the coral that has been
            bitten off by the main oral jaws.
          </p>
          <p>
            Many species of fish have secondary pharyngeal jaws. A
            particularly striking example is the <a
            href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moray_eel">Moray
            eel</a>, shown below, which launches its pharyngeal jaws
