<SubSection title = "Full linkage model" id = "full_linkage_model">
        <p>
          The linkage model below can have its geometry set either by
          the link lengths <InlineEquation equation = "(g, a, b, f)"/> or by the excess
          quantities <InlineEquation equation = "(T_1, T_2, T_3)."/> Whether each of the <InlineEquation equation = "T_i"/>
          are positive or negative determines the type of input and
          output (crank, rocker, etc.). For example, if <InlineEquation equation = "T_3"/> is
          negative then <InlineEquation equation = "T_3 = f + b - g - a &lt; 0,"/> which means <InlineEquation equation = "g + a > f + b."/>
          This implies that the input angle <InlineEquation equation = "\\alpha"/>
          cannot rotate around to <InlineEquation equation = "180 ^ \\circ,"/> as <InlineEquation equation = "D"/> would be too far
          from <InlineEquation equation = "B,"/> and so the input rod can't be a crank and must be
          some type of rocker.
        </p>
        <p>
          Two other useful geometric quantities shown below are the
          Grashof index <InlineEquation equation = "G"/> and the validity index <InlineEquation equation = "V."/> If <InlineEquation equation = "G \gt 0"/>
          then the shortest link is able to fully rotate through
          <InlineEquation equation = "360 ^ \\circ"/> (the linkage is “Grashof”), while if <InlineEquation equation = "G \\lt 0"/>
          then the shortest link only reciprocates (the linkage is
          “non-Grashof”). If <InlineEquation equation = "V \\lt 0"/> then the linkage is impossible,
          as the longest link is longer than the total length of the
          other three links.
        </p>
